  <li id="comment-9889" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="https://www.blogger.com/profile/00788350116801648626" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Katie</a></cite></div>
      <a href="index.html?p=1375#comment-9889"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2009-12-05T19:12:52-05:00">Saturday, December 5, 2009 at 7:12 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>I also found these disappointing, but it may be my fault for making a substitution. They came out quite wet in the center, after 20 minutes in the oven. I substituted the southern self-rising flour with 2/3 c Wondra (as suggested) and 1 1/3 c AP flour (not suggested) with 1.5 tsp baking powder and a total of 1 tsp salt. So that&#39;s what NOT to do!</p>
<p>All substituting aside, I also found them WAY too sweet. They were, as another poster said above, like cake. Or muffins. Or pancakes. (But not biscuits!)</p>
<p>But I&#39;m going to try again, with the AP flour and Wondra&#8230; only up the salt to 1.5 tsp, the BP to 2 tsp, and decrease the sugar to a tablespoon. And if that doesn&#39;t work I am going to mail-order White Lily 🙂 (and still cut the sugar!)</p>
<p>Thanks for the recipe though!</p>
    </div>

